{"key":"processedPost-10800660","value":{"id":10800660,"first":10792775,"last":12085581,"when":1249432608,"utime":"08/05/09 03:36 AM","content":"Full colonization is necessary for pinning to begin, thus it can be considered a pinning trigger.&nbsp; This is often misunderstood.&nbsp; Outdoors, the mycelium runs up against natural barriers, such as the edge of the manure pile, a dry section, mold, etc., thus it senses it has fully colonized the <i>available substrate</i>.<br /><br />We see this indoors nearly every day when new growers ask why their 90% colonized jars are pinning.&nbsp; The answer is that either the other ten percent is contaminated, or too dry, too wet, etc., thus full colonization of the available substrate has been achieved.<br />RR","title":"Re: Bulk trays... Fruiting when 100% colonized vs. Consolidation"}}